6. “Gor’Thak tilts its massive head, and its silver-white mane flares like ghost-fire. A deep, almost sad growl: ‘I was beautiful once. Now I am honest.’”

7. “The floating golden armor plates spin faster, creating a humming sound. The message: ‘The forge is dead. So is your hope. We are the same.’”

8. “A slow, deliberate swipe of a magenta claw through the air, leaving a glowing trail. The translation: ‘That line is where your enchantment ends. And your body begins.’”

9. “The creature opens its jaw wide, revealing rows of jagged fangs and the two golden tusks. A deafening silence follows, then a single word in a forgotten tongue: ‘Run.’ (It means the opposite.)”

10. “As it prepares to charge, a final telepathic burst: ‘When I sunder you, I will not forget you. I will carry your rage inside my mane. Thank you for the fuel.’”

Thank‑you note: Dearest Gor’Thak, Sunder‑Flame, you magnificent engine of righteous fury. I thank you for allowing me to stand within the crackling radius of your violet aura without being reduced to a smear of unmade magic. Your tusks are terrifying, your claws are the stuff of nightmares, and your tail should be classified as a natural disaster. But I confess I am most grateful for your honesty—you do not pretend to be anything other than what you are: a broken guardian who chose rage over despair. I will never look at a floating piece of golden armor the same way again. May your mane never stop burning, may your enemies always have enchantments worth sundering, and may you one day find a forge that does not betray you. Until then, roar loudly. With paradoxical admiration, your chronicler.

